{"title_page": "Hindu units of time", "text_new": "{{redirect|Srishti|the 1976 Indian Malayalam film|Srishti (film)}}\n{{short description|Hindu units of time}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}}\n\n[[Hindu]] texts describe units of [[time|\u0915\u0932\u093e]] measurements, from ''microseconds'' to ''Trillions'' of years.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pHiKycrLmEQC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Units of Measurement: Past, Present and Future. International System of Units|publisher=Springer|page=3|author=S.V. Gupta|isbn=9783642007385|date=3 November 2009}}</ref> According to these texts, time is cyclic, which repeats itself forever.<ref>{{cite book|title=Lost Discoveries: The Ancient Roots of Modern Science--from the Baby|author=Dick Teresi|page=174|publisher=SimonandSchuster}}</ref>\n\n==Time units==\n[[Image:HinduMeasurements.svg|thumb|200px|Hindu measurements in [[logarithm]]ic scale.]]\nVarious fragments of time are used in Hindu Scriptures like [[Vedas]], [[Bhagavata Purana]], [[Vishnu Puran]], [[Mahabharata]], [[Suryasidhanta]] etc. A summary of the Hindu metrics of time (''{{IAST|k\u0101la}} vyavah\u0101ra'') follows.{{Citation needed|reason=Previously cited book cites a personal blog which is not available anymore|date=September 2018}}\n\n===Sidereal metrics===\n\n{| class=wikitable\n!colspan=2| Unit !! Definition !! Relation to SI units\n|-\n! Truti || \u0924\u094d\u0930\u0941\u091f\u093f\n| [[Base unit (measurement)|Base unit]] || \u2248 0.30 \u00b5s\n|-\n! Renu || \u0930\u0947\u0923\u0941\n| 60 Truti || \u2248 18 \u00b5s\n|-\n! Lava  || \u0932\u0935\n| 60 Renu || \u2248 1080 \u00b5s\n|-\n! L\u012bk\u1e63aka || \u0932\u0940\u0915\u094d\u0937\u0915\n| 60 Lava || \u2248 64.8 [[Millisecond|ms]]\n|-\n! Lipta || \u0932\u093f\u092a\u094d\u0924\u093e\n|rowspan=2| 64.8Leekshaka ||rowspan=2| \u2248 4.2 s\n|-\n! Vipala || \u0935\u093f\u092a\u0932                   =30 s\n|-\n! {{IAST|Pala}} || \u092a\u0932\n|rowspan=3| 60 Lipta ||rowspan=3| \u2248 30 s\n|-\n! {{IAST|Vigha\u1e6di}} || \u0935\u093f\u0918\u091f\u093f\n|-\n! {{IAST|Vin\u0101d\u012b}} || \u0935\u093f\u0928\u093e\u0921\u0940\n|-\n! {{IAST|Gha\u1e6di}} || \u0918\u091f\u093f\n|rowspan=3| 31 Vigha\u1e6di || rowspan=3| \u2248 1.86 [[Orders of magnitude (time)|ks]]\n|-\n! {{IAST|N\u0101d\u012b}} || \u0928\u093e\u0921\u0940\n|-\n! {{IAST|Danda}} || \u0926\u0923\u094d\u0921\n|-\n! {{IAST|Muh\u016brta}} || \u092e\u0941\u0939\u0942\u0930\u094d\u0924\n| 2 Gha\u1e6di || \u2248 3.72 ks\n|-\n! rowspan=2| Nak\u1e63hatra Ahor\u0101tram (Sidereal Day)|| rowspan=2| \u0928\u0915\u094d\u0937\u0924\u094d\u0930 \u0905\u0939\u094b\u0930\u093e\u0924\u094d\u0930\u092e\u094d || 62Gha\u1e6d\u012b || \u2248 86.4 ks\n|-\n! 32Muh\u016brta || \u2248 86.4 ks\n|-\n|}\n\n==== According to S\u016brya Siddh\u0101nta <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://veda.wikidot.com/vedic-time-system|title=Vedic Time System - \u0935\u0947\u0926 Veda|website=veda.wikidot.com|access-date=2019-12-04}}</ref> ====\n{| class=wikitable\n|-\n! Unit !! Definition !! Relation to SI units\n|-\n! Truti \n| Base unit || \u2248 29.6 \u00b5s\n|-\n! Tatpara \n| 100 Truti || \u2248 2.96 ms\n|-\n! Nimesha \n| 30 Tatpara || \u2248 88.9 ms\n|-\n! K\u0101\u1e63\u1e6dh\u0101\n| 18 Nimesha || \u2248 1.6 s\n|-\n! Kal\u0101\n| 30 K\u0101\u1e63\u1e6dh\u0101 || \u2248 48 s\n|-\n!Ghatika\n|30 Kal\u0101\n|\u2248 1.44 ks\n|-\n! Muh\u016brta\n| 2 Ghatika || \u2248 2.88 ks\n|-\n! Ahor\u0101tram (Sidereal Day)\n| 30 Muh\u016brta || \u2248 86.4 ks\n|-\n|}\n\n====Small units of time used in the Vedas====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Unit !! Definition !! Relation to SI units\n|-\n| ''Param\u0101\u1e47u''|| Base unit || \u2248 25 \u00b5s\n|-\n| ''A\u1e47u''|| 2 Param\u0101\u1e47u || \u2248 50 \u00b5s\n|-\n| ''Trasare\u1e47u''|| 3 A\u1e47u || \u2248 151 \u00b5s\n|-\n| ''Tru\u1e6di''|| 3 Trasare\u1e47u || \u2248 454 \u00b5s\n|-\n| ''Vedha''|| 100 Tru\u1e6di || \u2248 45 ms\n|-\n| ''Lava''|| 3 Vedha || \u2248 0.14 s\n|-\n| ''Nime\u1e63a''|| 3 Lava || \u2248 0.4 s\n|-\n| ''K\u1e63a\u1e47a''|| 3 Nimesha || \u2248 1.22 s\n|-\n| ''K\u0101\u1e63\u1e6dh\u0101''|| 5 K\u1e63a\u1e47a || \u2248 6 s\n|-\n| ''Laghu'' || 15 K\u0101\u1e63\u1e6dh\u0101 || \u2248 92 s\n|-\n| ''Danda''|| 15 Laghu || \u2248 1.38 ks\n|-\n| ''Muh\u016brta''||\t2 Danda|| \u2248 2.76 ks\n|-\n| ''Ahor\u0101tram''|| 31 Muh\u016brta || \u2248 86.4 ks\n|-\n! Masa (Month) || 30 Ahor\u0101tram || \u2248 2592 ks\n|-\n! Ritu (Season) || 2 Masa || \u2248 5184 ks\n|- \n! Ayana || 3 Ritu || \u2248 15552 ks\n|-\n! Samvatsara (Year)\n|rowspan=2| 2 Ayana ||rowspan=2| \u2248 31104 ks<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=pHiKycrLmEQC&pg=PA5&dq=Truti+lava#v=onepage&q=Truti%20lava&f=false|title=Units of Measurement: Past, Present and Future. International System of Units|publisher=Springer|page=5|author=S.V. Gupta|isbn=9783642007385|date=3 November 2009}}</ref>\n|-\n! Ahor\u0101tram of Deva\n|}\n\n==Lunar metrics==\n* A ''[[Tithi]]'' or [[lunar day]] is defined as the time it takes for the [[longitude|longitudinal]] [[angle]] between the [[moon]] and the Sun to increase by 12[[degree (angle)|\u00b0]].Tithis begin at varying times of day and vary in duration from approximately 19 to approximately 26 hours.<ref name=\"S.V. Gupta 5,6\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pHiKycrLmEQC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Units of Measurement: Past, Present and Future. International System of Units|publisher=Springer|page=5,6|author=S.V. Gupta|isbn=9783642007385|date=3 November 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite book| last = Kumar| first = Ashwini| title = Vaastu: The Art And Science Of Living| url =https://books.google.com/books?id=PwlmRgLt7WkC&pg=PA50| date = 2005| publisher = Sterling Publishers Pvt. Ltd| isbn = 81-207-2569-7| page = 50 }}</ref>\n* A ''Paksa'' (also ''[[paksha|{{IAST|Pak\u1e63a}}]]'') or [[lunar fortnight]] consists of 15 tithes.<ref name=\"S.V. Gupta 5,6\"/>\n* A ''[[Masa|{{IAST|M\u0101sa}}]]'' or [[lunar month]] (30days) is divided into 2 ''[[paksha|{{IAST|Pak\u1e63a}}]]''s: the one between [[new moon]] and [[full moon]] (waxing) is called ''gaura'' or (bright) or ''[[shukla paksha|{{IAST|\u015aukla Pak\u1e63a}}]]''; the one between full moon and new moon (waning) ''K\u1e5bi\u1e63h\u1e47a'' (dark) ''paksha''<ref name=\"S.V. Gupta 5,6\"/>\n* A ''[[Ritu (Hindu calendar)|{{IAST|\u1e5aitu}}]]'' (or ''season'') is 2 ''[[masa|{{IAST|M\u0101sa}}]]''<ref name=\"S.V. Gupta 5,6\"/>\n* An ''Ayana'' is 3 [[Ritu (Hindu calendar)|{{IAST|\u1e5aitu}}]]s<ref name=\"S.V. Gupta 5,6\"/>\n* A year is two ''Ayanas''<ref name=\"S.V. Gupta 5,6\"/>\n\n==Tropical metrics==\n* A ''Y\u0101ma'' = {{1/4}} of a day (light) or night  = {{frac|7|1|2}} Ghatis (\u0918\u091f\u093f) =  {{frac|3|3|4}} ''Muhurta''s = 3 '''[[Hour|{{IAST|Hora}}]]'''s (\u0939\u094b\u0930\u093e)''tely 24 hours.<ref name=\"S.V. Gupta 6\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pHiKycrLmEQC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Units of Measurement: Past, Present and Future. International System of Units|publisher=Springer|page=6|author=S.V. Gupta|isbn=9783642007385|date=3 November 2009}}</ref>\n* Eight ''Y\u0101mas'' make a full day (day + night)<ref name=\"S.V. Gupta 6\"/>\n* An ''Ahor\u0101tra'' is a tropical day (Note: A day is considered to begin and end at sunrise, not midnight.)<ref name=\"S.V. Gupta 6\"/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=2| Name !! Definition !! Equivalence\n|-\n| ''Yama'' || \u092f\u093e\u092e || {{1/4}} of a day (light) or night || \u2248 3 hours\n|-\n! S\u0101vana Ahor\u0101tram || \u0938\u093e\u0935\u0928 \u0905\u0939\u094b\u0930\u093e\u0924\u094d\u0930\u092e\u094d || 8 Yamas || 1 Solar day\n|-\n|}\n\n==Reckoning of time among other entities==\n===Among the Pit\u1e5bs (''forefathers'')===\n\n* 1 day of pitras = 1 solar ''masa'' (month) <ref name=\"S.V. Gupta 6\"/>\n* 30 days of pitras = 1 month of pitras<ref name=\"S.V. Gupta 6\"/>\n* 12 months of pitras = 1 year of pitras<ref name=\"S.V. Gupta 6\"/>\nThe Lifespan of the pitras is 100 years of pitras (3,000 Solar years).<ref name=\"S.V. Gupta 6\"/>\n\n===Among the Devas===\n\nThe life span of any Hindu [[Deva (Hinduism)|deva]] spans nearly (or more than) 4.5&nbsp;million years. Statistically, we can also look it as:\n* 12000 Deva Years = Life Span of Devas = 1 Mah\u0101-Yuga.<ref name=\"Hans Kng 50\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=sm0BfUKwct0C&pg=PA50&lpg=PA50&dq=4,000+%2B+400+%2B+400+%3D+4,800+divine+years+(%3D+1,728,000+human+years)#v=onepage&q=4%2C000%20%2B%20400%20%2B%20400%20%3D%204%2C800%20divine%20years%20(%3D%201%2C728%2C000%20human%20years)&f=false|title=Tracing The Way: Spiritual Dimensions of the World Religions|publisher=[[A&C Black]]|page=50|author=Hans Kng|isbn=9780826494238|date=31 October 2006}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Vishnu Purana|{{IAST|Vi\u1e63\u1e47u Pur\u0101\u1e47a}}]] Time measurement section of the [[Vishnu Purana|{{IAST|Vi\u1e63\u1e47u Pur\u0101\u1e47a}}]] Book I Chapter III explains the above as follows:\n* 2 Ayanas (6-month periods, see above) = 1 human year or 1 day of the devas\n* 4,000 + 400 + 400 = 4,800 divine years (= 1,728,000 human years) = 1 [[Satya Yuga]]<ref name=\"Hans Kng 50\"/>\n* 3,000 + 300 + 300 = 3,600 divine years (= 1,296,000 human years) = 1 [[Treta Yuga]]<ref name=\"Hans Kng 50\"/>\n* 2,000 + 200 + 200 = 2,400 divine years (= 864,000 human years) = 1 [[Dvapara Yuga]]<ref name=\"Hans Kng 50\"/>\n* 1,000 + 100 + 100 = 1,200 divine years (= 432,000 human years) = 1 [[Kali Yuga]]<ref name=\"Hans Kng 50\"/>\n* 12,000 divine year = 4 Yugas (= 4,320,000 human years) = 1 Mah\u0101-Yuga (also is equaled to 12000 Daiva (divine) Yuga)<ref name=\"Hans Kng 50\"/>\n* [2*12,000 = 24,000 divine year = 12000 revolutions of sun around its dual]<ref name=\"Hans Kng 50\"/>\n\n===For Brahma===\n* 1000 Mah\u0101-Yugas = 1 Kalpa = 1 day of Brahma\n(2 ''Kalpas'' constitute a day and night of Brahma, 8.64&nbsp;billion human years)\n* 30 days of Brahma = 1 month of Brahma (259.2&nbsp;billion human years)\n* 12 months of Brahma = 1 year of Brahma (3.1104&nbsp;trillion human years)\n* 50 years of Brahma = 1 Par\u0101rdha (156,764,160,000,000 human years)\n* 2 parardhas = 100 years of Brahma = 1 Para = 1 Mah\u0101-Kalpa (the lifespan of Brahma) (313,528,320,000,000 human years)\n\nOne day of Brahma is divided into 10000 parts called ''chara\u1e47as''.<ref name=\"Bryan E. Penprase 182\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pQHNDgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Power of Stars|publisher=Springer|page=182|author=Bryan E. Penprase|isbn=9783319525976|date=5 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Four Yugas ==\n\nThe four yugas which come one after the other are as follows (along with their durations):\n\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible\"\n|+ The Four Yugas\n|-\n| 4 chara\u1e47as (1,728,000 [[solar year]]s) || [[Satya Yuga]]\n|-\n| 3 chara\u1e47as (1,296,000 solar years) || [[Treta Yuga]]\n|-\n| 2 chara\u1e47as (864,000 solar years) || [[Dvapara Yuga]]\n|-\n| 1 chara\u1e47as (432,000 solar years) || [[Kali Yuga]]\n|-\n| colspan=2 style=\"font-size: 88%\" | Source: [https://web.archive.org/web/20120222065203/http://vedabase.net/sb/3/11/19/en1]\n|}\n\n<timeline>\nPreset = TimeHorizontal_AutoPlaceBars_UnitYear\nImageSize = width:800\n\nColors =\n  id:satyayuga value:green legend:Satya-yuga\n  id:tretayuga value:rgb(0.5,0.5,1) legend:Treta-yuga\n  id:dvaparayuga value:yellow legend:Dvapara-yuga\n  id:kaliyuga value:red legend:Kali-yuga\n\n  id:canvas value:rgb(0.97,0.97,0.97)\n  id:grid1  value:rgb(0.86,0.86,0.86)\n  id:grid2  value:gray(0.8)\n  \nBackgroundColors = canvas:canvas\n\nPeriod = from:432 till:5616\n\nLegend = columns:1 left:70 top:20 columnwidth:300\n\nBarData=\n  barset:Fil\u00f2sofs\n\nDefine $bold= fontsize:M shift:(10,-7)\n\nPlotData=\n\n# set defaults\n  width:15 fontsize:S textcolor:black align:left anchor:from shift:(10,-4) color:grid1\n\n  barset:Fil\u00f2sofs\n\n  from:432 till:864 color:satyayuga fontsize:M text:\"[[Matsya]]\"        #from 432\n \n from:864  till:1296 color:satyayuga fontsize:M text:\"[[Kurma]]\"       \n \n from:1296  till:1728 color:satyayuga fontsize:M text:\"[[Varaha]]\"\n\n from:1728 till:2160 color:satyayuga fontsize:M text:\"[[Narasimha]]\"       \n \n from:2160 till:2592 color:tretayuga fontsize:M text:\"[[Vamana]]\"\n\n from:2592 till:3024 color:tretayuga fontsize:M text:\"[[Parashurama]]\"\n\n from:3024 till:3456 color:tretayuga fontsize:M text:\"[[Rama]]\"\n\n from:3456 till:3888 color:dvaparayuga fontsize:M text:\"[[Krishna]]\"\n\n \n from:4320 till:4752 color:kaliyuga fontsize:M text:\"[[Kalki]]\"\n\n</timeline>\n\nThe cycle repeats itself, so altogether there are 1,000 cycles of Mah\u0101-Yuga in one day of Brahma.\n\n:*One cycle of the above four ''Yuga''s is one '''Mah\u0101-Yuga''' (4.32&nbsp;million [[solar year]]s)\n:*as is confirmed by the G\u012bt\u0101 \u015ahloka 8.17 (statement) \"sahasra-yuga-paryantam ahar yad brahma\u1e47o vidu\u1e25 r\u0101tri\u1e41 yuga-sahasr\u0101nt\u0101\u1e41 te 'ho-r\u0101tra-vido jan\u0101\u1e25\", meaning, a day of brahma is of 1000 Mah\u0101-Yugas. Thus a day of Brahma, Kalpa, is of duration: 4.32 billion solar years. Two ''Kalpa''s constitute a day and night (Adhi Sandhi) of [[Brahma (god)|Brahma]].<ref>{{cite book|url=http://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/chapter/8/verse/17|title=Bhagavad Gita The Song of God|author=Swami Mukundananda}}</ref>\n:*A ''Manvantara'' consists of 71 Mah\u0101-Yuga (306,720,000 solar years). Each Manvantara is ruled by a Manu.<ref name=\"Bryan E. Penprase 182\"/>\n:*After each Manvantara follows one ''[[Sandhi|{{IAST|Sa\u1e43dhi}}]] K\u0101la'' of the same duration as a ''K\u1e5bta Yuga'' (1,728,000 = 4 Chara\u1e47as). (It is said that during a [[Sandhi|{{IAST|Sa\u1e43dhi}}]] K\u0101la, the entire earth is submerged in water.)<ref name=\"Bryan E. Penprase 182\"/>\n:*A ''[[Kalpa (aeon)|Kalpa]]'' consists of a period of 4.32 Billion solar years followed by 14 Manvataras and [[Sandhi|{{IAST|Sa\u1e43dhi}}]] Kalas.<ref name=\"Bryan E. Penprase 182\"/>\n:* A day of Brahma equals\n::(14 times 71 Mah\u0101-Yuga) + (15 \u00d7 4 Chara\u1e47as)\n::= 994 Mah\u0101-Yuga  +  (15 \u00d7 4800)\n::= 994 Mah\u0101-Yuga + (72,000 years)[deva years] \u00f7 6 = 12,000 [deva years] viz. one maha yuga.\n::= 994 Mah\u0101-Yuga + 6 Mah\u0101-Yuga\n::= 1,000 Mah\u0101-Yuga.<ref name=\"Bryan E. Penprase 182\"/>\n\n== Significance of the \"Four-Yuga\" system ==\n\nThe \"Four-Yuga\" structure, more popular as \"''Chaturyuga''\" system, actually attempts to describe the history of human evolution. In modern times, the prevailing theory of \"''Survival of the Fittest''\" tells us that the human beings are a result of gradual evolution process starting from single-cell living beings. But the \"''Chaturyuga''\" system mentions about the declining journey of human beings across the ages. In \"Satya Yuga\", the human beings were at its peak. Then it gradually came down throughout Treta and Dwapara yuga. In Kali Yuga, it is supposed to hit the lowest possible stature. If we go by the ancient scriptures, they specify that the start and end of each of the \"Yuga\" was marked by astronomical alignments. At the beginning of Treta Yuga, 5 planets resided in \"Aries\" constellation.At the end of last \"Dwapara\" yuga, the \"Saptarshi\" constellation (Ursa major), resided in \"Magha\" constellation. At the end of ongoing Kali-Yuga, Sun, Moon and Jupiter is said to reside in \"Pushya\" sector simultaneously.<sup>[''[https://legendofbharatbarsha.home.blog/2019/12/07/detailed-history-of-time/ Source]'']</sup>\n\n==Current date==\n\nCurrently, 50 years of Brahma have elapsed. The last Kalpa at the end of the 50th year is called Padma Kalpa. We are currently in the first 'day' of the 51st year.<ref>Burgess, Chapter 1, Verse 21</ref> This Brahma's day, Kalpa is named as Shveta-Varaha Kalpa. Within this Day, six Manvantaras have already elapsed<ref name=\"Burgess, Chapter 1, Verse 22\">Burgess, Chapter 1, Verse 22</ref> and this is the seventh Manvantara, named as \u2013 Vaivasvatha Manvantara (or Sraddhadeva Manvantara). Within the Vaivasvatha Manvantara, 27 Mahayugas<ref name=\"Burgess, Chapter 1, Verse 22\"/> (4 Yugas together is a Mahayuga), and the Krita,<ref>Burgess, Chapter 1, Verse 23</ref> Treta and Dwapara Yugas of the 28th Mahayuga have elapsed. This Kaliyuga is in the 28th Mahayuga. This Kaliyuga began in the year 3102 BCE in the proleptic Julian Calendar.<ref name=\"Burgess, p17\">Burgess, p17</ref> Since 50 years of Brahma have already elapsed, this is the second Parardha, also called as Dvithiya Parardha.\n\n===Calculating the elapsed time since current Brahma's creation===\n \n432000 \u00d7 10 \u00d7 1000 \u00d7 2 = 8.64&nbsp;billion years (2 Kalpa (day and night))\n \n8.64 \u00d7 10<sup>9</sup> \u00d7 30 \u00d7 12 = 3.1104 Trillion Years (1 year of Brahma)<br />3.1104 \u00d7 10<sup>12</sup> \u00d7 50 = 155.52&nbsp;trillion years (50 years of Brahma)\n \n(6 \u00d7 71 \u00d7 4320000) + 7 \u00d7 1.728 \u00d7 10<sup>6</sup> = 1852416000 years elapsed in first six Manvataras, and Sandhi Kalas in the current [[Kalpa (aeon)|Kalpa]]\n \n27 \u00d7 4320000 = 116640000 years elapsed in first 27 Mahayugas of the current Manvantara\n \n1.728 \u00d7 10^6 + 1.296 \u00d7 10<sup>6</sup> + 864000 = 3888000 years elapsed in current Mahayuga\n \n3102 + 2019 = 5121 years elapsed in current Kaliyuga.\n \nSo the total time elapsed since current Brahma is\n \n155520000000000 + 1852416000 + 116640000 + 3888000 + 5119 = '''''155,521,972,949,120 years'''''\n\n(one hundred fifty-five trillion, five hundred twenty-one billion, nine hundred seventy-two million, nine hundred forty-nine thousand, one hundred twenty years) as of 2020 AD\n\nTotal age of Brahma is 100 (Brahma Years) which is equal to '''''311,040,000,000,000 Human years'''''\n \nThe current Kali Yuga began at midnight 17 February / 18 February in 3102 BCE in the [[proleptic Julian calendar]].<ref>Burgess, Ebenezer [https://books.google.com/books?id=jpE7AAAAcAAJ&printsec=frontcover ''Translation of the S\u00fbrya-Siddh\u00e2nta: A text-book of Hindu astronomy, with notes and an appendix''] Originally published: ''Journal of the American Oriental Society'' '''6''' (1860) 141\u2013498 , p17\"</ref> As per the information above about Yuga periods, only 5,120 years are passed out of 432,000 years of current Kali Yuga, and hence another 426,880 years are left to complete this 28th Kali Yuga of Vaivaswatha Manvantara.{{refn|group=note|According to [[Sri Yukteswar Giri]], guru of [[Paramahansa Yogananda]],  The ascending phase of the Kali Yuga began in September 499 CE. Since September 1699, we have been in the ascending phase of the Dwapara Yuga. According to Sri Yukteswar, nobody wanted to announce the bad news of the beginning of the descending Kali Yuga, so they kept adding years to the Dvapara date (at that time 2400 Dvapara) only retitling the epoch to Kali.{{sfn|Yukteswar|1949}}}}\n\n'''Another way to calculate the universe's (Brahma's) lifespan is by converting mahayugas to kalpas.'''\n\n1000 mahayugas is equal to one day (kalpa) of Lord [[Brahma]]. His night (kalpa) is of equal duration. So, the entire day-night (24 hrs) of Brahma lasts for: \n\n4,320,000 * 1000 * 2 = '''8,640,000,000 years'''\n\nLord Brahma lives for 100 of his 360-day years which lasts for: \n\n8,640,000,000 * 360 * 100 = '''311,040,000,000,000 years'''\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal bar|Astronomy|History|Philosophy|Hinduism|Religion|Mythology}}\n{{col div|colwidth=30em}}\n*[[Age of the universe]]\n*[[Hindu cosmology]]\n*[[Hindu astronomy]]\n*[[Hindu calendar]]\n*[[Indian mathematics]]\n*[[Indian science and technology]]\n*[[Indian weights and measures]]\n*[[Jyotish]]\n*[[List of numbers in Hindu scriptures]]\n*[[Universe]]\n*[[Vedanga Jyotisha]]\n*[[Vedas]]\n*[[Yojana]]\n*[[Tamil units of measurement]]\n*[[Tamil months]]\n{{colend}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n*Victor J. Katz. ''A History of Mathematics: An Introduction'', 1998.\n\n==External links==\n*[https://legendofbharatbarsha.home.blog/2019/12/07/detailed-history-of-time/ Scientific Explanation of Hindu Time Units]\n*[http://www.wilbourhall.org/pdfs/suryaEnglish.pdf Translation of the Surya Siddhanta] (1861)\n* [https://twitter.com/Hinduism4u Daily Hindu Calendar]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070219000941/http://www.originofculture.com/Astronomical%20Cycles%20%26%20Facts.htm Exegesis of Hindu Cosmological Time Cycles]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050320030038/http://www.thearchimedeandual.com/platonic/Eastern/surya_siddanta_commentary/surya_siddhanta.htm Surya Siddhanta, Chapter I with Commentary and Illustrations]\n* [http://www.khapre.org/also/VedicTimeConverter.aspx Vedic Time Converter]\n\n{{Navboxes|list=\n{{Chronology}}\n{{Time in religion and mythology}}\n{{systems of measurement}}\n{{Brahmanda}}\n}}\n\n[[Category:Hindu astronomy]]\n[[Category:History of mathematics]]\n[[Category:Vedic period]]\n[[Category:Hindu philosophical concepts]]\n[[Category:Obsolete units of measurement]]\n[[Category:Units of time]]\n[[Category:Hindu calendar]]\n[[Category:Units of measurement by country]]\n[[Category:Time in India]]\n[[Category:Time in Nepal]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|Srishti|the 1976 Indian Malayalam film|Srishti (film)}}\n{{short description|Hindu units of time}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}}\n\n[[Hindu]] texts describe units of [[time|Kala]] measurements, from ''microseconds'' to ''Trillions'' of years.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pHiKycrLmEQC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Units of Measurement: Past, Present and Future. International System of Units|publisher=Springer|page=3|author=S.V. Gupta|isbn=9783642007385|date=3 November 2009}}</ref> According to these texts, time is cyclic, which repeats itself forever.<ref>{{cite book|title=Lost Discoveries: The Ancient Roots of Modern Science--from the Baby|author=Dick Teresi|page=174|publisher=SimonandSchuster}}</ref>\n\n==Time units==\n[[Image:HinduMeasurements.svg|thumb|200px|Hindu measurements in [[logarithm]]ic scale.]]\nVarious fragments of time are used in Hindu Scriptures like [[Vedas]], [[Bhagavata Purana]], [[Vishnu Puran]], [[Mahabharata]], [[Suryasidhanta]] etc. A summary of the Hindu metrics of time (''{{IAST|k\u0101la}} vyavah\u0101ra'') follows.{{Citation needed|reason=Previously cited book cites a personal blog which is not available anymore|date=September 2018}}\n\n===Sidereal metrics===\n\n{| class=wikitable\n!colspan=2| Unit !! Definition !! Relation to SI units\n|-\n! Truti || \u0924\u094d\u0930\u0941\u091f\u093f\n| [[Base unit (measurement)|Base unit]] || \u2248 0.30 \u00b5s\n|-\n! Renu || \u0930\u0947\u0923\u0941\n| 60 Truti || \u2248 18 \u00b5s\n|-\n! Lava  || \u0932\u0935\n| 60 Renu || \u2248 1080 \u00b5s\n|-\n! L\u012bk\u1e63aka || \u0932\u0940\u0915\u094d\u0937\u0915\n| 60 Lava || \u2248 64.8 [[Millisecond|ms]]\n|-\n! Lipta || \u0932\u093f\u092a\u094d\u0924\u093e\n|rowspan=2| 64.8Leekshaka ||rowspan=2| \u2248 4.2 s\n|-\n! Vipala || \u0935\u093f\u092a\u0932                   =30 s\n|-\n! {{IAST|Pala}} || \u092a\u0932\n|rowspan=3| 60 Lipta ||rowspan=3| \u2248 30 s\n|-\n! {{IAST|Vigha\u1e6di}} || \u0935\u093f\u0918\u091f\u093f\n|-\n! {{IAST|Vin\u0101d\u012b}} || \u0935\u093f\u0928\u093e\u0921\u0940\n|-\n! {{IAST|Gha\u1e6di}} || \u0918\u091f\u093f\n|rowspan=3| 31 Vigha\u1e6di || rowspan=3| \u2248 1.86 [[Orders of magnitude (time)|ks]]\n|-\n! {{IAST|N\u0101d\u012b}} || \u0928\u093e\u0921\u0940\n|-\n! {{IAST|Danda}} || \u0926\u0923\u094d\u0921\n|-\n! {{IAST|Muh\u016brta}} || \u092e\u0941\u0939\u0942\u0930\u094d\u0924\n| 2 Gha\u1e6di || \u2248 3.72 ks\n|-\n! rowspan=2| Nak\u1e63hatra Ahor\u0101tram (Sidereal Day)|| rowspan=2| \u0928\u0915\u094d\u0937\u0924\u094d\u0930 \u0905\u0939\u094b\u0930\u093e\u0924\u094d\u0930\u092e\u094d || 62Gha\u1e6d\u012b || \u2248 86.4 ks\n|-\n! 32Muh\u016brta || \u2248 86.4 ks\n|-\n|}\n\n==== According to S\u016brya Siddh\u0101nta <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://veda.wikidot.com/vedic-time-system|title=Vedic Time System - \u0935\u0947\u0926 Veda|website=veda.wikidot.com|access-date=2019-12-04}}</ref> ====\n{| class=wikitable\n|-\n! Unit !! Definition !! Relation to SI units\n|-\n! Truti \n| Base unit || \u2248 29.6 \u00b5s\n|-\n! Tatpara \n| 100 Truti || \u2248 2.96 ms\n|-\n! Nimesha \n| 30 Tatpara || \u2248 88.9 ms\n|-\n! K\u0101\u1e63\u1e6dh\u0101\n| 18 Nimesha || \u2248 1.6 s\n|-\n! Kal\u0101\n| 30 K\u0101\u1e63\u1e6dh\u0101 || \u2248 48 s\n|-\n!Ghatika\n|30 Kal\u0101\n|\u2248 1.44 ks\n|-\n! Muh\u016brta\n| 2 Ghatika || \u2248 2.88 ks\n|-\n! Ahor\u0101tram (Sidereal Day)\n| 30 Muh\u016brta || \u2248 86.4 ks\n|-\n|}\n\n====Small units of time used in the Vedas====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Unit !! Definition !! Relation to SI units\n|-\n| ''Param\u0101\u1e47u''|| Base unit || \u2248 25 \u00b5s\n|-\n| ''A\u1e47u''|| 2 Param\u0101\u1e47u || \u2248 50 \u00b5s\n|-\n| ''Trasare\u1e47u''|| 3 A\u1e47u || \u2248 151 \u00b5s\n|-\n| ''Tru\u1e6di''|| 3 Trasare\u1e47u || \u2248 454 \u00b5s\n|-\n| ''Vedha''|| 100 Tru\u1e6di || \u2248 45 ms\n|-\n| ''Lava''|| 3 Vedha || \u2248 0.14 s\n|-\n| ''Nime\u1e63a''|| 3 Lava || \u2248 0.4 s\n|-\n| ''K\u1e63a\u1e47a''|| 3 Nimesha || \u2248 1.22 s\n|-\n| ''K\u0101\u1e63\u1e6dh\u0101''|| 5 K\u1e63a\u1e47a || \u2248 6 s\n|-\n| ''Laghu'' || 15 K\u0101\u1e63\u1e6dh\u0101 || \u2248 92 s\n|-\n| ''Danda''|| 15 Laghu || \u2248 1.38 ks\n|-\n| ''Muh\u016brta''||\t2 Danda|| \u2248 2.76 ks\n|-\n| ''Ahor\u0101tram''|| 31 Muh\u016brta || \u2248 86.4 ks\n|-\n! Masa (Month) || 30 Ahor\u0101tram || \u2248 2592 ks\n|-\n! Ritu (Season) || 2 Masa || \u2248 5184 ks\n|- \n! Ayana || 3 Ritu || \u2248 15552 ks\n|-\n! Samvatsara (Year)\n|rowspan=2| 2 Ayana ||rowspan=2| \u2248 31104 ks<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=pHiKycrLmEQC&pg=PA5&dq=Truti+lava#v=onepage&q=Truti%20lava&f=false|title=Units of Measurement: Past, Present and Future. International System of Units|publisher=Springer|page=5|author=S.V. Gupta|isbn=9783642007385|date=3 November 2009}}</ref>\n|-\n! Ahor\u0101tram of Deva\n|}\n\n==Lunar metrics==\n* A ''[[Tithi]]'' or [[lunar day]] is defined as the time it takes for the [[longitude|longitudinal]] [[angle]] between the [[moon]] and the Sun to increase by 12[[degree (angle)|\u00b0]].Tithis begin at varying times of day and vary in duration from approximately 19 to approximately 26 hours.<ref name=\"S.V. Gupta 5,6\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pHiKycrLmEQC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Units of Measurement: Past, Present and Future. International System of Units|publisher=Springer|page=5,6|author=S.V. Gupta|isbn=9783642007385|date=3 November 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite book| last = Kumar| first = Ashwini| title = Vaastu: The Art And Science Of Living| url =https://books.google.com/books?id=PwlmRgLt7WkC&pg=PA50| date = 2005| publisher = Sterling Publishers Pvt. Ltd| isbn = 81-207-2569-7| page = 50 }}</ref>\n* A ''Paksa'' (also ''[[paksha|{{IAST|Pak\u1e63a}}]]'') or [[lunar fortnight]] consists of 15 tithes.<ref name=\"S.V. Gupta 5,6\"/>\n* A ''[[Masa|{{IAST|M\u0101sa}}]]'' or [[lunar month]] (30days) is divided into 2 ''[[paksha|{{IAST|Pak\u1e63a}}]]''s: the one between [[new moon]] and [[full moon]] (waxing) is called ''gaura'' or (bright) or ''[[shukla paksha|{{IAST|\u015aukla Pak\u1e63a}}]]''; the one between full moon and new moon (waning) ''K\u1e5bi\u1e63h\u1e47a'' (dark) ''paksha''<ref name=\"S.V. Gupta 5,6\"/>\n* A ''[[Ritu (Hindu calendar)|{{IAST|\u1e5aitu}}]]'' (or ''season'') is 2 ''[[masa|{{IAST|M\u0101sa}}]]''<ref name=\"S.V. Gupta 5,6\"/>\n* An ''Ayana'' is 3 [[Ritu (Hindu calendar)|{{IAST|\u1e5aitu}}]]s<ref name=\"S.V. Gupta 5,6\"/>\n* A year is two ''Ayanas''<ref name=\"S.V. Gupta 5,6\"/>\n\n==Tropical metrics==\n* A ''Y\u0101ma'' = {{1/4}} of a day (light) or night  = {{frac|7|1|2}} Ghatis (\u0918\u091f\u093f) =  {{frac|3|3|4}} ''Muhurta''s = 3 '''[[Hour|{{IAST|Hora}}]]'''s (\u0939\u094b\u0930\u093e)''tely 24 hours.<ref name=\"S.V. Gupta 6\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pHiKycrLmEQC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Units of Measurement: Past, Present and Future. International System of Units|publisher=Springer|page=6|author=S.V. Gupta|isbn=9783642007385|date=3 November 2009}}</ref>\n* Eight ''Y\u0101mas'' make a full day (day + night)<ref name=\"S.V. Gupta 6\"/>\n* An ''Ahor\u0101tra'' is a tropical day (Note: A day is considered to begin and end at sunrise, not midnight.)<ref name=\"S.V. Gupta 6\"/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=2| Name !! Definition !! Equivalence\n|-\n| ''Yama'' || \u092f\u093e\u092e || {{1/4}} of a day (light) or night || \u2248 3 hours\n|-\n! S\u0101vana Ahor\u0101tram || \u0938\u093e\u0935\u0928 \u0905\u0939\u094b\u0930\u093e\u0924\u094d\u0930\u092e\u094d || 8 Yamas || 1 Solar day\n|-\n|}\n\n==Reckoning of time among other entities==\n===Among the Pit\u1e5bs (''forefathers'')===\n\n* 1 day of pitras = 1 solar ''masa'' (month) <ref name=\"S.V. Gupta 6\"/>\n* 30 days of pitras = 1 month of pitras<ref name=\"S.V. Gupta 6\"/>\n* 12 months of pitras = 1 year of pitras<ref name=\"S.V. Gupta 6\"/>\nThe Lifespan of the pitras is 100 years of pitras (3,000 Solar years).<ref name=\"S.V. Gupta 6\"/>\n\n===Among the Devas===\n\nThe life span of any Hindu [[Deva (Hinduism)|deva]] spans nearly (or more than) 4.5&nbsp;million years. Statistically, we can also look it as:\n* 12000 Deva Years = Life Span of Devas = 1 Mah\u0101-Yuga.<ref name=\"Hans Kng 50\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=sm0BfUKwct0C&pg=PA50&lpg=PA50&dq=4,000+%2B+400+%2B+400+%3D+4,800+divine+years+(%3D+1,728,000+human+years)#v=onepage&q=4%2C000%20%2B%20400%20%2B%20400%20%3D%204%2C800%20divine%20years%20(%3D%201%2C728%2C000%20human%20years)&f=false|title=Tracing The Way: Spiritual Dimensions of the World Religions|publisher=[[A&C Black]]|page=50|author=Hans Kng|isbn=9780826494238|date=31 October 2006}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Vishnu Purana|{{IAST|Vi\u1e63\u1e47u Pur\u0101\u1e47a}}]] Time measurement section of the [[Vishnu Purana|{{IAST|Vi\u1e63\u1e47u Pur\u0101\u1e47a}}]] Book I Chapter III explains the above as follows:\n* 2 Ayanas (6-month periods, see above) = 1 human year or 1 day of the devas\n* 4,000 + 400 + 400 = 4,800 divine years (= 1,728,000 human years) = 1 [[Satya Yuga]]<ref name=\"Hans Kng 50\"/>\n* 3,000 + 300 + 300 = 3,600 divine years (= 1,296,000 human years) = 1 [[Treta Yuga]]<ref name=\"Hans Kng 50\"/>\n* 2,000 + 200 + 200 = 2,400 divine years (= 864,000 human years) = 1 [[Dvapara Yuga]]<ref name=\"Hans Kng 50\"/>\n* 1,000 + 100 + 100 = 1,200 divine years (= 432,000 human years) = 1 [[Kali Yuga]]<ref name=\"Hans Kng 50\"/>\n* 12,000 divine year = 4 Yugas (= 4,320,000 human years) = 1 Mah\u0101-Yuga (also is equaled to 12000 Daiva (divine) Yuga)<ref name=\"Hans Kng 50\"/>\n* [2*12,000 = 24,000 divine year = 12000 revolutions of sun around its dual]<ref name=\"Hans Kng 50\"/>\n\n===For Brahma===\n* 1000 Mah\u0101-Yugas = 1 Kalpa = 1 day of Brahma\n(2 ''Kalpas'' constitute a day and night of Brahma, 8.64&nbsp;billion human years)\n* 30 days of Brahma = 1 month of Brahma (259.2&nbsp;billion human years)\n* 12 months of Brahma = 1 year of Brahma (3.1104&nbsp;trillion human years)\n* 50 years of Brahma = 1 Par\u0101rdha (156,764,160,000,000 human years)\n* 2 parardhas = 100 years of Brahma = 1 Para = 1 Mah\u0101-Kalpa (the lifespan of Brahma) (313,528,320,000,000 human years)\n\nOne day of Brahma is divided into 10000 parts called ''chara\u1e47as''.<ref name=\"Bryan E. Penprase 182\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pQHNDgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Power of Stars|publisher=Springer|page=182|author=Bryan E. Penprase|isbn=9783319525976|date=5 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Four Yugas ==\n\nThe four yugas which come one after the other are as follows (along with their durations):\n\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible\"\n|+ The Four Yugas\n|-\n| 4 chara\u1e47as (1,728,000 [[solar year]]s) || [[Satya Yuga]]\n|-\n| 3 chara\u1e47as (1,296,000 solar years) || [[Treta Yuga]]\n|-\n| 2 chara\u1e47as (864,000 solar years) || [[Dvapara Yuga]]\n|-\n| 1 chara\u1e47as (432,000 solar years) || [[Kali Yuga]]\n|-\n| colspan=2 style=\"font-size: 88%\" | Source: [https://web.archive.org/web/20120222065203/http://vedabase.net/sb/3/11/19/en1]\n|}\n\n<timeline>\nPreset = TimeHorizontal_AutoPlaceBars_UnitYear\nImageSize = width:800\n\nColors =\n  id:satyayuga value:green legend:Satya-yuga\n  id:tretayuga value:rgb(0.5,0.5,1) legend:Treta-yuga\n  id:dvaparayuga value:yellow legend:Dvapara-yuga\n  id:kaliyuga value:red legend:Kali-yuga\n\n  id:canvas value:rgb(0.97,0.97,0.97)\n  id:grid1  value:rgb(0.86,0.86,0.86)\n  id:grid2  value:gray(0.8)\n  \nBackgroundColors = canvas:canvas\n\nPeriod = from:432 till:5616\n\nLegend = columns:1 left:70 top:20 columnwidth:300\n\nBarData=\n  barset:Fil\u00f2sofs\n\nDefine $bold= fontsize:M shift:(10,-7)\n\nPlotData=\n\n# set defaults\n  width:15 fontsize:S textcolor:black align:left anchor:from shift:(10,-4) color:grid1\n\n  barset:Fil\u00f2sofs\n\n  from:432 till:864 color:satyayuga fontsize:M text:\"[[Matsya]]\"        #from 432\n \n from:864  till:1296 color:satyayuga fontsize:M text:\"[[Kurma]]\"       \n \n from:1296  till:1728 color:satyayuga fontsize:M text:\"[[Varaha]]\"\n\n from:1728 till:2160 color:satyayuga fontsize:M text:\"[[Narasimha]]\"       \n \n from:2160 till:2592 color:tretayuga fontsize:M text:\"[[Vamana]]\"\n\n from:2592 till:3024 color:tretayuga fontsize:M text:\"[[Parashurama]]\"\n\n from:3024 till:3456 color:tretayuga fontsize:M text:\"[[Rama]]\"\n\n from:3456 till:3888 color:dvaparayuga fontsize:M text:\"[[Krishna]]\"\n\n \n from:4320 till:4752 color:kaliyuga fontsize:M text:\"[[Kalki]]\"\n\n</timeline>\n\nThe cycle repeats itself, so altogether there are 1,000 cycles of Mah\u0101-Yuga in one day of Brahma.\n\n:*One cycle of the above four ''Yuga''s is one '''Mah\u0101-Yuga''' (4.32&nbsp;million [[solar year]]s)\n:*as is confirmed by the G\u012bt\u0101 \u015ahloka 8.17 (statement) \"sahasra-yuga-paryantam ahar yad brahma\u1e47o vidu\u1e25 r\u0101tri\u1e41 yuga-sahasr\u0101nt\u0101\u1e41 te 'ho-r\u0101tra-vido jan\u0101\u1e25\", meaning, a day of brahma is of 1000 Mah\u0101-Yugas. Thus a day of Brahma, Kalpa, is of duration: 4.32 billion solar years. Two ''Kalpa''s constitute a day and night (Adhi Sandhi) of [[Brahma (god)|Brahma]].<ref>{{cite book|url=http://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/chapter/8/verse/17|title=Bhagavad Gita The Song of God|author=Swami Mukundananda}}</ref>\n:*A ''Manvantara'' consists of 71 Mah\u0101-Yuga (306,720,000 solar years). Each Manvantara is ruled by a Manu.<ref name=\"Bryan E. Penprase 182\"/>\n:*After each Manvantara follows one ''[[Sandhi|{{IAST|Sa\u1e43dhi}}]] K\u0101la'' of the same duration as a ''K\u1e5bta Yuga'' (1,728,000 = 4 Chara\u1e47as). (It is said that during a [[Sandhi|{{IAST|Sa\u1e43dhi}}]] K\u0101la, the entire earth is submerged in water.)<ref name=\"Bryan E. Penprase 182\"/>\n:*A ''[[Kalpa (aeon)|Kalpa]]'' consists of a period of 4.32 Billion solar years followed by 14 Manvataras and [[Sandhi|{{IAST|Sa\u1e43dhi}}]] Kalas.<ref name=\"Bryan E. Penprase 182\"/>\n:* A day of Brahma equals\n::(14 times 71 Mah\u0101-Yuga) + (15 \u00d7 4 Chara\u1e47as)\n::= 994 Mah\u0101-Yuga  +  (15 \u00d7 4800)\n::= 994 Mah\u0101-Yuga + (72,000 years)[deva years] \u00f7 6 = 12,000 [deva years] viz. one maha yuga.\n::= 994 Mah\u0101-Yuga + 6 Mah\u0101-Yuga\n::= 1,000 Mah\u0101-Yuga.<ref name=\"Bryan E. Penprase 182\"/>\n\n== Significance of the \"Four-Yuga\" system ==\n\nThe \"Four-Yuga\" structure, more popular as \"''Chaturyuga''\" system, actually attempts to describe the history of human evolution. In modern times, the prevailing theory of \"''Survival of the Fittest''\" tells us that the human beings are a result of gradual evolution process starting from single-cell living beings. But the \"''Chaturyuga''\" system mentions about the declining journey of human beings across the ages. In \"Satya Yuga\", the human beings were at its peak. Then it gradually came down throughout Treta and Dwapara yuga. In Kali Yuga, it is supposed to hit the lowest possible stature. If we go by the ancient scriptures, they specify that the start and end of each of the \"Yuga\" was marked by astronomical alignments. At the beginning of Treta Yuga, 5 planets resided in \"Aries\" constellation.At the end of last \"Dwapara\" yuga, the \"Saptarshi\" constellation (Ursa major), resided in \"Magha\" constellation. At the end of ongoing Kali-Yuga, Sun, Moon and Jupiter is said to reside in \"Pushya\" sector simultaneously.<sup>[''[https://legendofbharatbarsha.home.blog/2019/12/07/detailed-history-of-time/ Source]'']</sup>\n\n==Current date==\n\nCurrently, 50 years of Brahma have elapsed. The last Kalpa at the end of the 50th year is called Padma Kalpa. We are currently in the first 'day' of the 51st year.<ref>Burgess, Chapter 1, Verse 21</ref> This Brahma's day, Kalpa is named as Shveta-Varaha Kalpa. Within this Day, six Manvantaras have already elapsed<ref name=\"Burgess, Chapter 1, Verse 22\">Burgess, Chapter 1, Verse 22</ref> and this is the seventh Manvantara, named as \u2013 Vaivasvatha Manvantara (or Sraddhadeva Manvantara). Within the Vaivasvatha Manvantara, 27 Mahayugas<ref name=\"Burgess, Chapter 1, Verse 22\"/> (4 Yugas together is a Mahayuga), and the Krita,<ref>Burgess, Chapter 1, Verse 23</ref> Treta and Dwapara Yugas of the 28th Mahayuga have elapsed. This Kaliyuga is in the 28th Mahayuga. This Kaliyuga began in the year 3102 BCE in the proleptic Julian Calendar.<ref name=\"Burgess, p17\">Burgess, p17</ref> Since 50 years of Brahma have already elapsed, this is the second Parardha, also called as Dvithiya Parardha.\n\n===Calculating the elapsed time since current Brahma's creation===\n \n432000 \u00d7 10 \u00d7 1000 \u00d7 2 = 8.64&nbsp;billion years (2 Kalpa (day and night))\n \n8.64 \u00d7 10<sup>9</sup> \u00d7 30 \u00d7 12 = 3.1104 Trillion Years (1 year of Brahma)<br />3.1104 \u00d7 10<sup>12</sup> \u00d7 50 = 155.52&nbsp;trillion years (50 years of Brahma)\n \n(6 \u00d7 71 \u00d7 4320000) + 7 \u00d7 1.728 \u00d7 10<sup>6</sup> = 1852416000 years elapsed in first six Manvataras, and Sandhi Kalas in the current [[Kalpa (aeon)|Kalpa]]\n \n27 \u00d7 4320000 = 116640000 years elapsed in first 27 Mahayugas of the current Manvantara\n \n1.728 \u00d7 10^6 + 1.296 \u00d7 10<sup>6</sup> + 864000 = 3888000 years elapsed in current Mahayuga\n \n3102 + 2019 = 5121 years elapsed in current Kaliyuga.\n \nSo the total time elapsed since current Brahma is\n \n155520000000000 + 1852416000 + 116640000 + 3888000 + 5119 = '''''155,521,972,949,120 years'''''\n\n(one hundred fifty-five trillion, five hundred twenty-one billion, nine hundred seventy-two million, nine hundred forty-nine thousand, one hundred twenty years) as of 2020 AD\n\nTotal age of Brahma is 100 (Brahma Years) which is equal to '''''311,040,000,000,000 Human years'''''\n \nThe current Kali Yuga began at midnight 17 February / 18 February in 3102 BCE in the [[proleptic Julian calendar]].<ref>Burgess, Ebenezer [https://books.google.com/books?id=jpE7AAAAcAAJ&printsec=frontcover ''Translation of the S\u00fbrya-Siddh\u00e2nta: A text-book of Hindu astronomy, with notes and an appendix''] Originally published: ''Journal of the American Oriental Society'' '''6''' (1860) 141\u2013498 , p17\"</ref> As per the information above about Yuga periods, only 5,120 years are passed out of 432,000 years of current Kali Yuga, and hence another 426,880 years are left to complete this 28th Kali Yuga of Vaivaswatha Manvantara.{{refn|group=note|According to [[Sri Yukteswar Giri]], guru of [[Paramahansa Yogananda]],  The ascending phase of the Kali Yuga began in September 499 CE. Since September 1699, we have been in the ascending phase of the Dwapara Yuga. According to Sri Yukteswar, nobody wanted to announce the bad news of the beginning of the descending Kali Yuga, so they kept adding years to the Dvapara date (at that time 2400 Dvapara) only retitling the epoch to Kali.{{sfn|Yukteswar|1949}}}}\n\n'''Another way to calculate the universe's (Brahma's) lifespan is by converting mahayugas to kalpas.'''\n\n1000 mahayugas is equal to one day (kalpa) of Lord [[Brahma]]. His night (kalpa) is of equal duration. So, the entire day-night (24 hrs) of Brahma lasts for: \n\n4,320,000 * 1000 * 2 = '''8,640,000,000 years'''\n\nLord Brahma lives for 100 of his 360-day years which lasts for: \n\n8,640,000,000 * 360 * 100 = '''311,040,000,000,000 years'''\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal bar|Astronomy|History|Philosophy|Hinduism|Religion|Mythology}}\n{{col div|colwidth=30em}}\n*[[Age of the universe]]\n*[[Hindu cosmology]]\n*[[Hindu astronomy]]\n*[[Hindu calendar]]\n*[[Indian mathematics]]\n*[[Indian science and technology]]\n*[[Indian weights and measures]]\n*[[Jyotish]]\n*[[List of numbers in Hindu scriptures]]\n*[[Universe]]\n*[[Vedanga Jyotisha]]\n*[[Vedas]]\n*[[Yojana]]\n*[[Tamil units of measurement]]\n*[[Tamil months]]\n{{colend}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n*Victor J. Katz. ''A History of Mathematics: An Introduction'', 1998.\n\n==External links==\n*[https://legendofbharatbarsha.home.blog/2019/12/07/detailed-history-of-time/ Scientific Explanation of Hindu Time Units]\n*[http://www.wilbourhall.org/pdfs/suryaEnglish.pdf Translation of the Surya Siddhanta] (1861)\n* [https://twitter.com/Hinduism4u Daily Hindu Calendar]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070219000941/http://www.originofculture.com/Astronomical%20Cycles%20%26%20Facts.htm Exegesis of Hindu Cosmological Time Cycles]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050320030038/http://www.thearchimedeandual.com/platonic/Eastern/surya_siddanta_commentary/surya_siddhanta.htm Surya Siddhanta, Chapter I with Commentary and Illustrations]\n* [http://www.khapre.org/also/VedicTimeConverter.aspx Vedic Time Converter]\n\n{{Navboxes|list=\n{{Chronology}}\n{{Time in religion and mythology}}\n{{systems of measurement}}\n{{Brahmanda}}\n}}\n\n[[Category:Hindu astronomy]]\n[[Category:History of mathematics]]\n[[Category:Vedic period]]\n[[Category:Hindu philosophical concepts]]\n[[Category:Obsolete units of measurement]]\n[[Category:Units of time]]\n[[Category:Hindu calendar]]\n[[Category:Units of measurement by country]]\n[[Category:Time in India]]\n[[Category:Time in Nepal]]\n", "name_user": "2001:8f8:1825:8a37:c4ab:31d2:5466:7a4b", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hindu_units_of_time"}
{"title_page": "Searchlight Pictures", "text_new": "{{short description|American film studio}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Searchlight Pictures\n| logo = File:Searchlight Pictures logo.svg\n| logo_caption = \n| type = [[Subsidiary]]\n| industry = [[Film industry|Film]]\n| former_name = Fox Searchlight Pictures (1994\u20132020)\n| founded = {{Start date and age|1994||}}\n| founder = [[Tom Rothman|Thomas Rothman]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=1498356&privcapId=6441777&previousCapId=91031&previousTitle=NEWS%20CORP-CLASS%20B|title=Executive Profile: Thomas E. Rothman|accessdate= 10 May 2013}}</ref>\n| hq_location = 10201 West Pico Boulevard<br>Building 38, 1st Floor\n| hq_location_city = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]]\n| hq_location_country = [[United States]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapId=22728079|title=Company Overview of Fox Searchlight Pictures, Inc.}}</ref>\n| area_served = Worldwide\n| key_people = {{ubl|Nancy Utley (Co-Chairman)|Stephen Gilula (Co-Chairman)}}\n| products = [[film|Motion pictures]]\n| revenue = {{profit}} [[United States dollar|$]]6.50 million (2007)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://biz.yahoo.com/ic/106/106290.htmlSymbol=TWX |title=Fox Searchlight Pictures Company Profile|website=Biz.yahoo.com|accessdate=18 July 2018}}</ref>\n| parent = [[Walt Disney Studios (division)|The Walt Disney Studios]]<!-- Per [[Template:Infobox company]], it states: \"Do not include any higher-level owners, like the parents' parent companies.\" -->\n| num_employees = 40\n| num_employees_year = \n| website = {{URL|www.searchlightpictures.com}}\n}} \n'''Fox Searchlight Pictures''' (now '''Searchlight Pictures''') is an American [[film studio]] that is a subsidiary of [[Walt Disney Studios (division)|The Walt Disney Studios]], a division of [[The Walt Disney Company]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2019/biz/news/disney-fox-deal-complete-1203167374/|title=Disney Completes 21st Century Fox Acquisition|last=Littleton|first=Cynthia|date=March 19, 2019|work=Variety|access-date=March 19, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"20thCenturyStudiosNYT\"/> It is a sister studio of the larger film studio [[20th Century Studios]].  Searchlight specializes in the production and distribution of [[independent film|independent]] [[North America]]n and [[Europe]]an films alongside [[comedy-drama]], horror, [[art-house]], and foreign films, all of which the studio sometimes finances.\n\nSearchlight's ''[[Slumdog Millionaire]]'', ''[[12 Years a Slave (film)|12 Years a Slave]]'', ''[[Birdman (film)|Birdman]]'', and ''[[The Shape of Water]]''  have all won the [[Academy Award for Best Picture]] at the [[81st Academy Awards|81st]], [[86th Academy Awards|86th]], [[87th Academy Awards|87th]], and [[90th Academy Awards|90th]] Academy Awards respectively, as well as a further 15 Academy Awards combined. Other Best Picture nominations include ''[[The Full Monty]]'', ''[[Sideways]]'', ''[[Little Miss Sunshine]]'', ''[[Juno (film)|Juno]]'', ''[[Black Swan (film)|Black Swan]]'', ''[[127 Hours]]'', ''[[The Tree of Life (film)|The Tree of Life]]'', ''[[The Descendants]]'', ''[[Beasts of the Southern Wild]]'', ''[[The Grand Budapest Hotel]]'', ''[[Brooklyn (film)|Brooklyn]]'', ''[[Three Billboards Outside Ebbing, Missouri]]'', ''[[The Favourite]]'' and ''[[Jojo Rabbit]]''. ''Slumdog Millionaire'' is the studio's largest commercial success, with over $377 million (US) of box office receipts, against a production budget of only $15 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=slumdogmillionaire.htm |work=[[Box Office Mojo]] |title=Slumdog Millionaire (2008)}}</ref>\n\nSearchlight Pictures was one of the [[21st Century Fox]] film production companies that was [[Acquisition of 21st Century Fox by Disney|acquired by Disney]] on March 20, 2019. Searchlight, however, continues to operate its own distribution unit for its films autonomously from [[Walt Disney Studios Motion Pictures|Disney's main distribution unit]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2020/01/emma-watts-leaves-disneys-20th-century-studios-1202846855/|title=Emma Watts Leaves Disney\u2019s 20th Century Studios|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|date=January 30, 2020|work=Deadline.com|access-date=February 3, 2020|url-status=live|quote=Post-merger, Fox Searchlight, now re-branded Searchlight Pictures, enjoys a lot of autonomy in the Disney empire, greenlighting pics they know and operating their own distribution, publicity and marketing teams. 20th Century Studios (which recently dropped the Fox) was melded into the bigger Disney fold, fusing all its operations.}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nFox Searchlight Pictures was founded in 1994 by [[Tom Rothman|Thomas Rothman]].<ref name=\"BW6\">{{cite web|url=http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=1498356&privcapId=6441777&previousCapId=91031&previousTitle=NEWS%20CORP-CLASS%20B|title=Executive Profile: Thomas E. Rothman|accessdate= 10 May 2013}}</ref> Prior to the creation of Searchlight, Fox previously released independent films and specialty releases under the banner of '''20th Century-Fox International Classics''', later renamed '''20th Century-Fox Specialized Film Division''', then '''TLC Films'''. The most notable of the releases under these banners include ''[[Suspiria]]'', ''[[Bill Cosby: Himself]]'', ''[[Eating Raoul]]'', ''[[The Gods Must Be Crazy]]'', ''[[Reuben, Reuben]]'', and ''[[Ziggy Stardust and the Spiders from Mars (film)|Ziggy Stardust and the Spiders from Mars]]''.<ref>Tzioumakis, Yannis (2012). ''Hollywood's Indies: Classics Divisions, Specialty Labels and the American Film Market'', pp. 55-58. [[Edinburgh University Press]].</ref>\n\nIn 2006, a companion label, [[Fox Atomic]], was created to produce and/or distribute genre films.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mediapost.com/publications/article/45787/fox-atomic-unveils-broadband-site.html?edition=|title=Fox Atomic Unveils Broadband Site|website=Mediapost.com|first=Mark|last=Walsh|date=July 20, 2006|accessdate=January 7, 2016}}</ref> Fox Atomic closed down in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/20th-century-fox-closing-fox-atomic-ross-6880/|title=20th Century Fox Closing Down Fox Atomic|website=ScreenRant.com|first=Ross|last=Miller|date=April 21, 2009|accessdate=January 7, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe [[acquisition of 21st Century Fox by Disney]] took place on March 20, 2019,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/disney-closes-fox-deal-creating-global-content-powerhouse-1174498 |title=Disney Closes $71.3 Billion Fox Deal, Creating Global Content Powerhouse |last=Szalai |first=Georg |last2=Bond |first2=Paul |date=March 20, 2019 |website=The Hollywood Reporter |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190320064742/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/disney-closes-fox-deal-creating-global-content-powerhouse-1174498 |archivedate=March 20, 2019 |accessdate=March 20, 2019}}</ref> including Fox Searchlight.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/03/disney-film-executives-post-merger-team-set-1202580586/ |title=After Trying Day, Disney Sets Film Leadership Lineup |last=Hipes |first=Patrick |date=March 21, 2019 |website=Deadline Hollywood |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190327101434/https://deadline.com/2019/03/disney-film-executives-post-merger-team-set-1202580586/ |archivedate=March 27, 2019 |accessdate=March 27, 2019 |quote=Fox Animation (including Blue Sky Studios) will continue to be led by Co-Presidents Andrea Miloro and Robert Baird.}}</ref>\n\nAs of November 2019, [[FX (TV channel)#FX Networks|FX]] and Fox Searchlight were assigned to supply [[Hulu]] with content.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Littleton |first1=Cynthia |last2=Littleton |first2=Cynthia |title=FX to Produce Original Series for Hulu as Brands Become More Closely Intertwined |url=https://variety.com/2019/biz/news/fx-hulu-disney-mrs-america-american-horror-story-1203397601/ |accessdate=March 11, 2020 |work=Variety |date=November 7, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> On January 17, 2020, it was announced that the \"Fox\" name would be dropped from several of the Fox assets that were acquired by Disney, shortening the company\u2019s name to \"Searchlight Pictures\", in favor to distance it from [[Fox Corporation]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/film/news/disney-dropping-fox-20th-century-studios-1203470349/|title=Disney Drops Fox Name, Will Rebrand as 20th Century Studios, Searchlight Pictures|first=Adam B.|last=Vary|work=Variety|date=January 17, 2020|accessdate=January 17, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"20thCenturyStudiosNYT\">{{cite web | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/17/business/media/disney-fox-name.html | title = Disney Drops Fox From Names of Studios It Bought From Rupert Murdoch | publisher = [[The New York Times]] | first = Brooks | last = Barnes | date = January 17, 2020 | accessdate  = January 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==List of releases==\n{{main|List of Searchlight Pictures films}}\n\n==Television==\nIn April 2018, the studio launched '''Searchlight Television''', broadening the variety of projects produced under the Searchlight banner. It is headed by David Greenbaum and Matthew Greenfield.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/04/fox-searchlight-television-division-hulu-david-greenbaum-matthew-greenfield-upped-to-production-presidents-for-film-tv-1202362441/|title=Searchlight Launches TV Division; David Greenbaum, Matthew Greenfield Upped To Production Presidents For Film, TV|last=Fleming|first=Mike|work=Deadline Hollywood|date=April 11, 2018|accessdate=July 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2018/04/fox-searchlight-television-prestige-tv-fx-netflix-disney-streaming-platform|title=What Searchlight\u2019s New TV Division Means for the Future of Prestige TV|last=Bradley|first=Laura|website=Vanityfair.com|accessdate=July 18, 2018}}</ref> Both original material and adaptations of Searchlight's existing film library will be produced for cable, streaming and broadcast television, in the form of documentaries, scripted series, limited series and more.  In April 2019, the [[Hulu]] streaming service ordered ''[[The Dropout (TV series)|The Dropout]]'', starring [[Kate McKinnon]] from Searchlight Television.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/04/the-dropout-hulu-limited-series-kate-mckinnon-star-elizabeth-holmes-fox-searchlight-television-abc-news-1202593032/|title=Hulu Orders \u2018The Dropout\u2019 Limited Series Starring Kate McKinnon As Elizabeth Holmes From Searchlight TV|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|last2=Andreeva|first2=Nellie|date=2019-04-10|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2019-05-07}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Disneynature]]\n* [[Hollywood Pictures]]\n* [[Touchstone Pictures]]\n* [[20th Century Studios]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|www.searchlightpictures.com}}\n* {{IMDb company|id=0028932|company=Searchlight Pictures}}\n\n{{Walt Disney Studios}}\n{{Disney}}\n{{Film Studio}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:American companies established in 1994]]\n[[Category:Film distributors of the United States]]\n[[Category:Film production companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Entertainment companies based in California]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Media companies established in 1994]]\n[[Category:Entertainment companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:1994 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:20th Century Studios]]\n[[Category:The Walt Disney Studios]]\n[[Category:Disney acquisitions]]\n[[Category:Disney production studios]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American film studio}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Searchlight Pictures\n| logo = File:Searchlight Pictures logo.svg\n| logo_caption = \n| type = [[Subsidiary]]\n| industry = [[Film industry|Film]]\n| former_name = Fox Searchlight Pictures (1994\u20132020)\n| founded = {{Start date and age|1994||}}\n| founder = [[Tom Rothman|Thomas Rothman]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=1498356&privcapId=6441777&previousCapId=91031&previousTitle=NEWS%20CORP-CLASS%20B|title=Executive Profile: Thomas E. Rothman|accessdate= 10 May 2013}}</ref>\n| hq_location = 10201 West Pico Boulevard<br>Building 38, 1st Floor\n| hq_location_city = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]]\n| hq_location_country = [[United States]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapId=22728079|title=Company Overview of Fox Searchlight Pictures, Inc.}}</ref>\n| area_served = Worldwide\n| key_people = {{ubl|Nancy Utley (Co-Chairman)|Stephen Gilula (Co-Chairman)}}\n| products = [[film|Motion pictures]]\n| revenue = {{profit}} [[United States dollar|$]]6.50 million (2007)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://biz.yahoo.com/ic/106/106290.htmlSymbol=TWX |title=Fox Searchlight Pictures Company Profile|website=Biz.yahoo.com|accessdate=18 July 2018}}</ref>\n| parent = [[Walt Disney Studios (division)|The Walt Disney Studios]]<!-- Per [[Template:Infobox company]], it states: \"Do not include any higher-level owners, like the parents' parent companies.\" -->\n| num_employees = 40\n| num_employees_year = \n| website = {{URL|www.searchlightpictures.com}}\n}} \n'''Searchlight Pictures''' (formerly '''Fox Searchlight Pictures''') is an American [[film studio]] that is a subsidiary of [[Walt Disney Studios (division)|The Walt Disney Studios]], a division of [[The Walt Disney Company]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2019/biz/news/disney-fox-deal-complete-1203167374/|title=Disney Completes 21st Century Fox Acquisition|last=Littleton|first=Cynthia|date=March 19, 2019|work=Variety|access-date=March 19, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"20thCenturyStudiosNYT\"/> It is a sister studio of the larger film studio [[20th Century Studios]].  Searchlight specializes in the production and distribution of [[independent film|independent]] [[North America]]n and [[Europe]]an films alongside [[comedy-drama]], horror, [[art-house]], and foreign films, all of which the studio sometimes finances.\n\nSearchlight's ''[[Slumdog Millionaire]]'', ''[[12 Years a Slave (film)|12 Years a Slave]]'', ''[[Birdman (film)|Birdman]]'', and ''[[The Shape of Water]]''  have all won the [[Academy Award for Best Picture]] at the [[81st Academy Awards|81st]], [[86th Academy Awards|86th]], [[87th Academy Awards|87th]], and [[90th Academy Awards|90th]] Academy Awards respectively, as well as a further 15 Academy Awards combined. Other Best Picture nominations include ''[[The Full Monty]]'', ''[[Sideways]]'', ''[[Little Miss Sunshine]]'', ''[[Juno (film)|Juno]]'', ''[[Black Swan (film)|Black Swan]]'', ''[[127 Hours]]'', ''[[The Tree of Life (film)|The Tree of Life]]'', ''[[The Descendants]]'', ''[[Beasts of the Southern Wild]]'', ''[[The Grand Budapest Hotel]]'', ''[[Brooklyn (film)|Brooklyn]]'', ''[[Three Billboards Outside Ebbing, Missouri]]'', ''[[The Favourite]]'' and ''[[Jojo Rabbit]]''. ''Slumdog Millionaire'' is the studio's largest commercial success, with over $377 million (US) of box office receipts, against a production budget of only $15 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=slumdogmillionaire.htm |work=[[Box Office Mojo]] |title=Slumdog Millionaire (2008)}}</ref>\n\nSearchlight Pictures was one of the [[21st Century Fox]] film production companies that was [[Acquisition of 21st Century Fox by Disney|acquired by Disney]] on March 20, 2019. Searchlight, however, continues to operate its own distribution unit for its films autonomously from [[Walt Disney Studios Motion Pictures|Disney's main distribution unit]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2020/01/emma-watts-leaves-disneys-20th-century-studios-1202846855/|title=Emma Watts Leaves Disney\u2019s 20th Century Studios|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|date=January 30, 2020|work=Deadline.com|access-date=February 3, 2020|url-status=live|quote=Post-merger, Fox Searchlight, now re-branded Searchlight Pictures, enjoys a lot of autonomy in the Disney empire, greenlighting pics they know and operating their own distribution, publicity and marketing teams. 20th Century Studios (which recently dropped the Fox) was melded into the bigger Disney fold, fusing all its operations.}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nFox Searchlight Pictures was founded in 1994 by [[Tom Rothman|Thomas Rothman]].<ref name=\"BW6\">{{cite web|url=http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=1498356&privcapId=6441777&previousCapId=91031&previousTitle=NEWS%20CORP-CLASS%20B|title=Executive Profile: Thomas E. Rothman|accessdate= 10 May 2013}}</ref> Prior to the creation of Searchlight, Fox previously released independent films and specialty releases under the banner of '''20th Century-Fox International Classics''', later renamed '''20th Century-Fox Specialized Film Division''', then '''TLC Films'''. The most notable of the releases under these banners include ''[[Suspiria]]'', ''[[Bill Cosby: Himself]]'', ''[[Eating Raoul]]'', ''[[The Gods Must Be Crazy]]'', ''[[Reuben, Reuben]]'', and ''[[Ziggy Stardust and the Spiders from Mars (film)|Ziggy Stardust and the Spiders from Mars]]''.<ref>Tzioumakis, Yannis (2012). ''Hollywood's Indies: Classics Divisions, Specialty Labels and the American Film Market'', pp. 55-58. [[Edinburgh University Press]].</ref>\n\nIn 2006, a companion label, [[Fox Atomic]], was created to produce and/or distribute genre films.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mediapost.com/publications/article/45787/fox-atomic-unveils-broadband-site.html?edition=|title=Fox Atomic Unveils Broadband Site|website=Mediapost.com|first=Mark|last=Walsh|date=July 20, 2006|accessdate=January 7, 2016}}</ref> Fox Atomic closed down in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/20th-century-fox-closing-fox-atomic-ross-6880/|title=20th Century Fox Closing Down Fox Atomic|website=ScreenRant.com|first=Ross|last=Miller|date=April 21, 2009|accessdate=January 7, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe [[acquisition of 21st Century Fox by Disney]] took place on March 20, 2019,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/disney-closes-fox-deal-creating-global-content-powerhouse-1174498 |title=Disney Closes $71.3 Billion Fox Deal, Creating Global Content Powerhouse |last=Szalai |first=Georg |last2=Bond |first2=Paul |date=March 20, 2019 |website=The Hollywood Reporter |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190320064742/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/disney-closes-fox-deal-creating-global-content-powerhouse-1174498 |archivedate=March 20, 2019 |accessdate=March 20, 2019}}</ref> including Fox Searchlight.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/03/disney-film-executives-post-merger-team-set-1202580586/ |title=After Trying Day, Disney Sets Film Leadership Lineup |last=Hipes |first=Patrick |date=March 21, 2019 |website=Deadline Hollywood |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190327101434/https://deadline.com/2019/03/disney-film-executives-post-merger-team-set-1202580586/ |archivedate=March 27, 2019 |accessdate=March 27, 2019 |quote=Fox Animation (including Blue Sky Studios) will continue to be led by Co-Presidents Andrea Miloro and Robert Baird.}}</ref>\n\nAs of November 2019, [[FX (TV channel)#FX Networks|FX]] and Fox Searchlight were assigned to supply [[Hulu]] with content.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Littleton |first1=Cynthia |last2=Littleton |first2=Cynthia |title=FX to Produce Original Series for Hulu as Brands Become More Closely Intertwined |url=https://variety.com/2019/biz/news/fx-hulu-disney-mrs-america-american-horror-story-1203397601/ |accessdate=March 11, 2020 |work=Variety |date=November 7, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> On January 17, 2020, it was announced that the \"Fox\" name would be dropped from several of the Fox assets that were acquired by Disney, shortening the company\u2019s name to \"Searchlight Pictures\", in favor to distance it from [[Fox Corporation]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/film/news/disney-dropping-fox-20th-century-studios-1203470349/|title=Disney Drops Fox Name, Will Rebrand as 20th Century Studios, Searchlight Pictures|first=Adam B.|last=Vary|work=Variety|date=January 17, 2020|accessdate=January 17, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"20thCenturyStudiosNYT\">{{cite web | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/17/business/media/disney-fox-name.html | title = Disney Drops Fox From Names of Studios It Bought From Rupert Murdoch | publisher = [[The New York Times]] | first = Brooks | last = Barnes | date = January 17, 2020 | accessdate  = January 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==List of releases==\n{{main|List of Searchlight Pictures films}}\n\n==Television==\nIn April 2018, the studio launched '''Searchlight Television''', broadening the variety of projects produced under the Searchlight banner. It is headed by David Greenbaum and Matthew Greenfield.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/04/fox-searchlight-television-division-hulu-david-greenbaum-matthew-greenfield-upped-to-production-presidents-for-film-tv-1202362441/|title=Searchlight Launches TV Division; David Greenbaum, Matthew Greenfield Upped To Production Presidents For Film, TV|last=Fleming|first=Mike|work=Deadline Hollywood|date=April 11, 2018|accessdate=July 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2018/04/fox-searchlight-television-prestige-tv-fx-netflix-disney-streaming-platform|title=What Searchlight\u2019s New TV Division Means for the Future of Prestige TV|last=Bradley|first=Laura|website=Vanityfair.com|accessdate=July 18, 2018}}</ref> Both original material and adaptations of Searchlight's existing film library will be produced for cable, streaming and broadcast television, in the form of documentaries, scripted series, limited series and more.  In April 2019, the [[Hulu]] streaming service ordered ''[[The Dropout (TV series)|The Dropout]]'', starring [[Kate McKinnon]] from Searchlight Television.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/04/the-dropout-hulu-limited-series-kate-mckinnon-star-elizabeth-holmes-fox-searchlight-television-abc-news-1202593032/|title=Hulu Orders \u2018The Dropout\u2019 Limited Series Starring Kate McKinnon As Elizabeth Holmes From Searchlight TV|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|last2=Andreeva|first2=Nellie|date=2019-04-10|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2019-05-07}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Disneynature]]\n* [[Hollywood Pictures]]\n* [[Touchstone Pictures]]\n* [[20th Century Studios]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|www.searchlightpictures.com}}\n* {{IMDb company|id=0028932|company=Searchlight Pictures}}\n\n{{Walt Disney Studios}}\n{{Disney}}\n{{Film Studio}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:American companies established in 1994]]\n[[Category:Film distributors of the United States]]\n[[Category:Film production companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Entertainment companies based in California]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Media companies established in 1994]]\n[[Category:Entertainment companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:1994 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:20th Century Studios]]\n[[Category:The Walt Disney Studios]]\n[[Category:Disney acquisitions]]\n[[Category:Disney production studios]]\n", "name_user": "120.29.66.119", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Searchlight_Pictures"}
{"title_page": "Big 12 Championship Game", "text_new": "{{for|the Big 12 men's basketball championship|Big 12 Men's Basketball Tournament}}\n{{Infobox NCAA conference tournament\n| name = Big 12 Championship Game\n| optional_subheader = Conference Football Championship\n| image = File:Dr Pepper Big 12 Football Championship.png\n| image_size = 250px\n| caption = Championship Game Logo\n| sport = [[American football|Football]]\n| conference = [[Big 12 Conference]]\n| number_of_teams = <!-- Only 2 compete in game, so it likely does not need to be put here -->\n| format =\n| current_stadium = [[AT&T Stadium]]\n| current_location = [[Arlington, Texas]]\n| years = 1996\u20132010; 2017\u2013present\n| most_recent = [[2019 Big 12 Championship Game|2019]]\n| current_champion = [[2019 Oklahoma Sooners football team|Oklahoma Sooners]]\n| most_championships = [[Oklahoma Sooners football|Oklahoma Sooners]] (10)\n| television = [[ESPN College Football on ABC|ABC]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.big12sports.com/ViewArticle.dbml?ATCLID=205680799|title=Big 12 Announces New Media Rights Deal With ESPN & FOX Sports Media Group|author=|date=|website=big12sports.com|accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref>\n| website = [https://big12sports.com/index.aspx?path=football big12sports.com]\n| sponsors = [[Dr Pepper]] (1996\u20132010, 2018\u2013present)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.big12sports.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=10410&ATCLID=1565606 |title=Dr Pepper Extends Corporate Partnership with Big 12 Conference |publisher=Big12sports.com: The Big 12 Conference Official Athletic Site |date=August 22, 2008 |accessdate=November 28, 2018}}</ref> <br>[[AT&T]] (2017)\n| all_stadiums =\n* [[The Dome at America's Center|Trans World Dome]] (1996, 1998)\n* [[Alamodome]] (1997, 1999, 2007)\n* [[Arrowhead Stadium]] (2000, 2003, 2004, 2006, 2008)\n* [[Texas Stadium]] (2001)\n* [[NRG Stadium|Reliant Stadium]] (2002, 2005)\n* [[AT&T Stadium]] (2009\u20132010, 2017\u20132021)\n| all_locations =\n* [[St. Louis]], [[Missouri]] (1996, 1998)\n* [[San Antonio]] (1997, 1999, 2007)\n* [[Kansas City, Missouri]] (2000, 2003, 2004, 2006, 2008)\n* [[Irving, Texas]] (2001)\n* [[Houston]], [[Texas]] (2002, 2005)\n* [[Arlington, Texas]] (2009, 2010, 2017\u20132021)\n}}\n{{OSM Location map      \n| nolabels = 1  \n| coord = {{coord|36.15|-90.72}}\n| zoom = 4\n| width = 400\n| height = 225\n| caption = [[File:Green pog.svg|10px]] \u2013 Championship Game\n| mark1 = Blue pog.svg\n| label1 = Baylor\n| mark-coord1 = {{coord|31.2255 |-97.0700 }}\n| label-pos1 = right\n| label-color1 = black\n| mark2 = Blue pog.svg\n| label2 = Iowa State\n| mark-coord2 = {{coord|42.023949 |-93.647595 }}\n| label-pos2 = top\n| label-color2 = black\n| mark3 = Blue pog.svg\n| label3 = Kansas\n| mark-coord3 = {{coord|38.5729 |-95.1452 }}\n| label-pos3 = right\n| label-color3 = black\n| mark4 = Blue pog.svg\n| label4 = Kansas State\n| mark-coord4 = {{coord|39.1130 |-96.3451 }}\n| label-pos4 = top\n| label-color4 = black\n| mark5 = Blue pog.svg\n| label5 = Oklahoma\n| mark-coord5 = {{coord|35.1231 |-97.2645 }}\n| label-pos5 = left\n| label-color5 = black\n| mark6 = Blue pog.svg\n| label6 = Oklahoma State\n| mark-coord6 = {{coord|36.0756 |-97.0451 }}\n| label-pos6 = top\n| label-color6 = black\n| mark7 = Blue pog.svg\n| label7 = TCU\n| mark-coord7 = {{coord|32.710 |-97.363 }}\n| label-pos7 = top\n| label-color7 = black\n| mark8 = Blue pog.svg\n| label8 = Texas\n| mark-coord8 = {{coord|30.285 |-97.735 }}\n| label-pos8 = bottom\n| label-color8 = black\n| mark9 = Blue pog.svg\n| label9 = Texas Tech\n| mark-coord9 = {{coord|33.584 |-101.878}}\n| label-pos9 = left\n| label-color9 = black\n| mark10 = Blue pog.svg\n| label10 = West Virginia\n| mark-coord10 = {{coord|39.3809 |-79.5716 }}\n| label-pos10 = top\n| label-color10 = black\n| mark11 = Green pog.svg\n| label11 = \n| mark-coord11 = {{coord|32.4452 |-97.534 }}\n| label-pos11 = top\n| label-color11 = black\n}}\nThe '''Big 12 Championship Game''' is a [[college football]] game held by the [[Big 12 Conference]]. The game was played each year since the conference's formation in 1996 until 2010 and returned during the 2017 season.  From 1996 to 2010 the championship game pitted the Big 12 North Division champion against the South Division champion in a game held after the regular season was completed.  From 2017 onward, the game features the two teams with the best conference records.\n\nThe Big 12 South led the series 11\u20134 and outscored the Big 12 North 463\u2013324 in the first 15 years the game was held.  In the first eight Big 12 championship games, from 1996 to 2003, the divisions split four games each, with the north champion winning in every odd-numbered year and the south champion winning in every even-numbered year.  However, the North division champion did not win after #13 Kansas State's 35\u20137 upset victory over #1 Oklahoma in 2003.\n\nThe game will be played at [[AT&T Stadium]] in [[Arlington, Texas]] until at least 2021.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.big12sports.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=10410&ATCLID=211669510 |title=Big 12 Announces 2018 Conference Football Schedule |publisher=Big12sports.com: The Big 12 Conference Official Athletic Site |date=October 26, 2017 |accessdate=October 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe first championship game was played after the 1996 regular season, the first year of play for the Big 12 (which was created from the merger of the [[Big Eight Conference]] and four teams from the [[Southwest Conference]]). Like the [[SEC Championship Game]] (which has been played since 1992), the game matched the winners of the conference's two six-team divisions. The championship game was held at several sites within the Big 12 states, with [[Arrowhead Stadium]] in [[Kansas City, Missouri]], hosting more often than any other venue.\n \nThe [[2008 Big 12 Championship Game]] was notable for the [[2008 Big 12 Conference South Division 3-way tie controversy|controversy over choosing the South Division representative]]. The [[2008 Oklahoma Sooners football team|Oklahoma Sooners]], [[2008 Texas Longhorns football team|Texas Longhorns]], and [[2008 Texas Tech Red Raiders football team|Texas Tech Red Raiders]] all finished with identical records and had each recorded a win and loss amongst one another. The Sooners earned a berth to the title game because they had the highest [[Bowl Championship Series]] ranking of the three at the time of selection. Oklahoma defeated the [[2008 Missouri Tigers football team|Missouri Tigers]] and earned a berth in the [[2009 BCS National Championship Game]].\n\nFrom 2009 through 2013, the game was scheduled to be played at Cowboys Stadium, now known as [[AT&T Stadium]], in [[Arlington, Texas]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.big12sports.com/ViewArticle.dbml?SPSID=106116&SPID=13135&DB_OEM_ID=10410&ATCLID=1521887 |title=Big 12 Conference Concludes Spring Meetings; Future Championship Sites Approved For Football, Basketball |publisher=Big12sports.com: The Big 12 Conference Official Athletic Site |date=May 24, 2007 |accessdate=June 21, 2010}}</ref> During June 2010, however, [[Nebraska Cornhuskers|Nebraska]] and [[Colorado Buffaloes|Colorado]] announced that they would [[2010\u201313 Big 12 Conference realignment|leave the Big 12]] for other conferences (the [[Big Ten Conference]] and the [[Pac-12 Conference]], respectively) in 2011. Because NCAA rules at the time required that a conference have 12 members in order to stage a football championship game that was exempt from NCAA limits on regular-season games, the conference dropped the championship game following the 2010 season. During this time, Oklahoma and Texas had expressed that a conference title game hurt the chances of the conference to have a representative in the [[BCS National Championship Game]], and now the [[College Football Playoff]], which started in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dallasnews.com/sharedcontent/dws/spt/colleges/topstories/stories/061610dnspobig12sider.20a83d0.html |title=UT coach Mack Brown not worried about lack of Big 12 title game |last=Carlton|first=Chuck|author2=Sabin, Rainer|date=June 16, 2010|work=[[The Dallas Morning News]]|accessdate=June 21, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100716171636/http://www.dallasnews.com/sharedcontent/dws/spt/colleges/topstories/stories/061610dnspobig12sider.20a83d0.html| archivedate= 16 July 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2014 after completing the first season with the College Football Playoff, [[2014 Baylor Bears football team|Baylor]] and [[2014 TCU Horned Frogs football team|TCU]] both finished the season with an 8\u20131 conference record and were declared co-champions by the conference despite Baylor's head-to-head win over TCU. When the selection committee met to set the teams for the first playoff, both Baylor and TCU were overlooked in favor of teams that competed in and won their conference's championship game, leaving the Big 12 out of the playoffs.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://espn.go.com/college-football/story/_/id/11992914/college-football-playoff-alabama-crimson-tide-oregon-ducks-florida-state-seminoles-ohio-state-buckeyes-inaugural-playoff | title=Ohio State bumps TCU from CFP | publisher=ESPN | date=December 12, 2014 | accessdate=May 4, 2015 |author1=Rovell, Darren  |author2=Purdum, David |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref> This led to criticism of how the Big 12 determined its champion.\n\nIn April 2015, legislation was developed by the [[Atlantic Coast Conference|ACC]] and the Big 12 to deregulate conference championship games. It was announced by NCAA officials as being expected to pass in time for the start of the 2016 season.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://espn.go.com/college-football/story/_/id/12814346/ohio-state-buckeyes-lock-no-1-spot-too-early-top-25 | title=Report: Conference title game deregulation expected by 2016 | publisher=ESPN | date=April 8, 2015 | accessdate=May 4, 2015}}</ref>  The legislation passed on January 14, 2016 allowing a conference with fewer than twelve teams to stage a championship game between the top two teams, so long as they play a round-robin schedule. In late 2016, the Big 12 decided to bring back the championship game in 2017 after a seven-year long gap of having no conference championship game.\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Results==\nBelow are the results from all Big 12 Championship Games played. The winning team appears in bold font, on a background of their primary team color. Rankings are from the [[AP Poll]] released prior to the game.\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!Year\n!colspan=\"2\"|North Division\n!colspan=\"2\"|South Division\n!Site\n!Attendance\n!MVP\n|- \n| [[1996 Big 12 Championship Game|1996]]\n| <small>3</small> [[1996 Nebraska Cornhuskers football team|Nebraska Cornhuskers]] || 27\n| style={{NCAA color cell|Texas Longhorns}}|<small></small> '''[[1996 Texas Longhorns football team|{{color|#FFFFFF|Texas Longhorns}}]]''' || '''37'''\n| [[The Dome at America's Center|Trans World Dome]] \u2022 [[St. Louis|St. Louis, MO]]\n| 63,109\n|align=left| RB DeAngelo Evans, Nebraska\n|- \n| [[1997 Big 12 Championship Game|1997]]\n| style={{NCAA color cell|Nebraska Cornhuskers}}|<small>2</small> '''[[1997 Nebraska Cornhuskers football team|{{color|#FFFFFF|Nebraska Cornhuskers}}]]''' || '''54'''\n| <small>14</small> [[1997 Texas A&M Aggies football team|Texas A&M Aggies]] || 15\n| [[Alamodome]] \u2022 [[San Antonio|San Antonio, TX]]\n| 64,824\n|align=left| RB [[Ahman Green]], Nebraska\n|- \n| [[1998 Big 12 Championship Game|1998]]\n| <small>2</small> [[1998 Kansas State Wildcats football team|Kansas State Wildcats]] || 33\n| style={{NCAA color cell|Texas A&M Aggies}}|<small>10</small> '''[[1998 Texas A&M Aggies football team|{{color|#FFFFFF|Texas A&M Aggies}}]]''' || '''36'''\n| Trans World Dome \u2022 St. Louis, MO\n| 60,798\n|align=left| QB Branndon Stewart, Texas A&M\n|- \n| [[1999 Big 12 Championship Game|1999]]\n| style={{NCAA color cell|Nebraska Cornhuskers}}|<small>3</small> '''[[1999 Nebraska Cornhuskers football team|{{color|#FFFFFF|Nebraska Cornhuskers}}]]''' || '''22'''\n| <small>12</small> [[1999 Texas Longhorns football team|Texas Longhorns]] || 6\n| Alamodome \u2022 San Antonio, TX\n| 65,035\n|align=left| \n|- \n| [[2000 Big 12 Championship Game|2000]]\n| <small>8</small> [[2000 Kansas State Wildcats football team|Kansas State Wildcats]] || 24\n| style={{NCAA color cell|Oklahoma Sooners}}|<small>1</small> '''[[2000 Oklahoma Sooners football team|{{color|#FFFFFF|Oklahoma Sooners}}]]''' || '''27'''\n| [[Arrowhead Stadium]] \u2022 [[Kansas City, Missouri|Kansas City, MO]]\n| 79,655\n|align=left| QB [[Josh Heupel]], Oklahoma\n|- \n| [[2001 Big 12 Championship Game|2001]]\n| style={{NCAA color cell|Colorado Buffaloes}}|<small>9</small> '''[[2001 Colorado Buffaloes football team|{{color|#FFFFFF|Colorado Buffaloes}}]]''' || '''39'''\n| <small>3</small> [[2001 Texas Longhorns football team|Texas Longhorns]] || 37\n| [[Texas Stadium]] \u2022 [[Irving, Texas|Irving, TX]]\n| 65,675\n|align=left| \n|- \n| [[2002 Big 12 Championship Game|2002]]\n| <small>12</small> [[2002 Colorado Buffaloes football team|Colorado Buffaloes]] || 7\n| style={{NCAA color cell|Oklahoma Sooners}}|<small>8</small> '''[[2002 Oklahoma Sooners football team|{{color|#FFFFFF|Oklahoma Sooners}}]]''' || '''29'''\n| [[NRG Stadium|Reliant Stadium]] \u2022 [[Houston|Houston, TX]]\n| 63,332\n|align=left| RB [[Quentin Griffin]], Oklahoma\n|- \n| [[2003 Big 12 Championship Game|2003]]\n| style={{NCAA color cell|Kansas State Wildcats}}|<small>13</small> '''[[2003 Kansas State Wildcats football team|{{color|#FFFFFF|Kansas State Wildcats}}]]''' || '''35'''\n| <small>1</small> [[2003 Oklahoma Sooners football team|Oklahoma Sooners]] || 7\n| rowspan=2| Arrowhead Stadium \u2022 Kansas City, MO\n| 75,491\n|align=left| QB [[Ell Roberson]], Kansas State\n|- \n| [[2004 Big 12 Championship Game|2004]]\n| <small></small> [[2004 Colorado Buffaloes football 